{
  "texts": [
    "Based on skeletal geometric features, Saha et al. [58] identified gestures corresponding to five basic human emotional states, including anger, fear, happiness, sadness, and relaxation.Researchers also studied the emotional expression of body language based on dimensional emotion models.",
    "Glowinski et al. [59] showed that essential groups of emotion, associated with the four quadrants of the valence-arousal space, can be distinguished from the representation of trajectories of head and hands from the frontal and lateral view of the body.",
    "The compact representations were grouped into clusters that divided the inputs into four categories based on their positions in the dimensional space, namely high-positive, high-negative, low-positive or low-negative.",
    "Kosti et al. [60] used features extracted from the body and background to study the intensity values, arousal, and dominance.",
    "Physiological ExpressionAlthough an individual may not clearly express his or her emotions through speech, gestures, or facial expressions, changes in physiological patterns are inevitable and detectable [61]."
  ]
}